The Information Regulator says TransUnion faces a possible hefty fine and has urged the credit bureau to provide greater transparency regarding the data breach. #eNCA's Govan Whittles has more details. #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Information Regulator says there have been ongoing engagements with TransUnion representatives after the company was hacked to assess the data breach and find possible solutions. Advocate Collen Weapond from Information Regulator says TransUnion could end up being fined up to R10-million. "It's important to stipulate there are eight conditions for unlawful processing of personal information that is entrusted to you,"Â Weapond said. WATCH | Discussion | Credit Bureau TransUnion hacked "Responsible parties including TransUnion are supposed to comply with those conditions. Failure which could result with the regulator investigating the security compromise which can result in a fine of up to R10-million or imprisonment of up to 10 years or compilation of both in terms of section 1/7 of the Protection of Personal Information Act. "TransUnion has approached international negotiators to start negotiating with the hackers and also approach international agencies to assist them as the threat hackers are outside of the country. Investigations are continuing. Information regulator was informed and gave constructive engagement to extend that we agreed on the way forward."